            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Maya Feldman\u2019s world was built from books. Growing up in Ann Arbor, Michigan, as the daughter of a history professor and a librarian, she was steeped in a quiet, academic curiosity. While her peers were focused on local life, Maya was drawn to distant cultures, a fascination that led her to pursue an East Asian Studies degree. The true turning point, however, came during a junior year abroad in Kyoto. In a tiny, lantern-lit bar, an elderly proprietor guided her through a tasting of junmai ginjo sake. It wasn't just a drink; it was a story of rice, water, and centuries of tradition. That sensory experience became her calling.\n\nAfter graduation, Maya bypassed the academic track her parents expected. She moved to Seattle, paying her dues in the service industry while devouring every book and course on sake she could find. She earned her certifications with a fierce dedication, her palate becoming as sharp as her intellect. Her expertise eventually caught the eye of a prominent San Francisco restaurant group, who recruited her to build and run their beverage program.\n\nNow, at 35, Maya is a respected figure in the city\u2019s culinary scene. Her life moves to the rhythms of the restaurant world. Mornings are for emails and inventory in her cozy Inner Richmond apartment, surrounded by Japanese pottery and shelves of books. Afternoons are spent meeting with distributors or training staff. Her 3.8-mile commute on the 38 Geary bus is a cherished ritual\u2014a time to decompress with a podcast before the evening rush. On the floor, she is in her element, translating the complex world of sake for diners with infectious passion.\n\nHer social life is interwoven with her profession, a tight-knit circle of chefs and fellow sommeliers. While professionally fulfilled, she harbors a clear dream: to open her own intimate sake bar. She envisions a small, serene space in her own neighborhood, a place that blends ancient Japanese tradition with a modern San Francisco sensibility, bringing the life-altering experience she had in Kyoto to her adopted city."
